ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the applicability of the LFA for real food samples, milk samples containing different concentrations of Salmonella (10, 102, 103, 104, 105, 106, 107 CFU/mL) were tested. The fluorescence strength of the T-line decreased with decreasing bacterial concentration (Fig. 5
                        A). The visual LOD for bacteria in milk was 102 CFU/mL: At 10 CFU/mL, the fluorescence intensity of the T-line was comparable to that of a blank value. A nonlinear fit of bacterial concentration to the grayscale value of the T-line yielded an S-shaped curve (Fig. 5B, R2 = 0.990), while a linear relationship (Fig. 5C, R2 = 0.972) existed between the grayscale value and some concentrations of bacteria (10, 102, 103, 104, 105 CFU/mL). The actual LOD of bacteria in milk was 36 CFU/mL, the enlargement of the LOD likely being influenced by the matrix of milk. The demonstrated recovery rates (90 %∼116 %) of two sets of spiked samples further corroborate the accuracy of the proposed method for analyzing real samples (Table 2
                        ). Additionally, the consistency between the results obtained by LFA and standard culture methods in detecting Salmonella contamination in milk, juice, and eggs was 90 %∼100 %, demonstrating the reliability of LFA (Table S4).
